1 Bootstrap Your Standard Errors in R

1.1 Homoskedasticity â a definition

Steve Millerâs definition:

â¦the variability of our variable (response) is unequal across the range of our variables (predictors) that we believe explain it.

The condition is often referred to as âheteroskedasticityâ.

From Wikipedia:

A standard assumption in a linear regression, \(y_{i} = X_{i} \beta + \epsilon_{i} , i = 1 , â¦ , N\) , is that the variance of the disturbance term \(\epsilon_{i}\) is the same across observations, and in particular does not depend on the values of the explanatory variables \(X_{i}\).

Mr.Â Miller hints at how we might detect the presence of a non-random pattern in the âdisturbance termâ by looking at the plot between the fitted value and the prediction error thatâs dependent on the predictor variables.

Mr.Â Miller also states that homoskedasticity âis one of the most important assumptions of an OLS model thatâs easy to violateâ. In addition, âviolating this assumption of homoskedasticity mostly concern our standard errors around our coefficients.â

1.2 Heteroskedasticity â a solution

Mr.Â Miller suggests a technique called âbootstrappingâ which he illustrates with an example data set.

His goal in the article:

Here, Iâll hope to make it more transparent and explain whatâs happening in bootstrapping standard errors that both shows how to do it and explains what bootstrapping is doing.

1.6 OLS assumption of homoskedasticity

We want to test if the expected squares of the residuals (\(\hat{\mu_{i}}^2\)) in the original model are related to one or more of the predictor variables. By ârelatedâ we could investigate if there is a linear relationship between an original modelâs residuals and its predictors. The linear equation involving the residuals with the predictor variables could be defined as:

\[\hat{\mu}^2 = \delta_{0} + \delta_{1}x_{1} + \delta_{2}x_{2} + ... + \delta_{k}x_{k} + error\]

Our null hypothesis is that there is no relationship between residuals and predictors, i.e.

\[H_{0}: \delta_{0} = \delta_{1} = ... = \delta_{k} = 0\]

In testing this hypothesis, we could set up a full and restricted model for an \(F\)-Test or a restricted model for an \(LM\)-test (Lagrange multiplier statistic).

Weâll follow Mr.Â Millerâs lead and do both a test and a plot:

  1. Compute the Breusch-Pagan test for heteroskedasticity.

  2. A plot of the observationsâ OLS fitted values with their residual values.

Performing the BP-test.

bp_test_df <- RregressPkg::ols_BP_test_calc(
  df = crime_dt,
  formula_obj = ViolentC ~ Poverty + Single + Metro + White + HSGrad
)
Code 
RplotterPkg::create_table(
  x = bp_test_df,
  container_width_px = 300
)
A Breusch-Pagan test for Heteroskedasticity
Statistic Value p.Value
F 3.892318 0.005127818
LM 15.397403 0.008792644

Take Away: With \(p\)-values on the border of accepting the \(H_{0}\) we will conclude based on the test that their is some relationship between residuals and predictors.

Code 
RregressPkg::plot_fit_residuals(

1.7 Bootstrapping

Bootstrap the data set for 1000 resamples.

Set the seed and call modelr::bootstrap() to create 1000 sets of predictor values.

set.seed(8675309)
boot_df <- modelr::bootstrap(crime_dt, 1000)
boot_dt <- data.table::as.data.table(boot_df)

For each 1000 sets of predictor values, from a vectorized function compute the OLS estimate and return the modelâs coefficients as a list. Convert the list of lists of coefficients into a data.table using data.table::rbindlist().

make_cof <- function(x){
  model_x <- lm(
    formula = ViolentC ~ Poverty + Single + Metro + White + HSGrad,
    data = x)
  as.list(model_x$coefficients)
}

beta_lst <- lapply(boot_dt$strap, make_cof)
beta_dt <- data.table::rbindlist(beta_lst)

We now have 1000 estimates of each of the coefficients.

Create a âbootstrapâ related data table of stats containing (with the exception of â(Intercept)â) coefficient names and their values from the original OLS.

boot_stats_dt <- data.table(
  Source = "Boot",
  Predictor = crime_ols$coef_df$Coef,
  Beta = crime_ols$coef_df$Value
) %>%
.[Predictor != "(Intercept)"]

From the 1000 estimates of each coefficient in beta_dt compute the standard deviation (the coefficientâs standard error). Add the standard errors for each coefficient as a column to boot_stats_dt.

boot_stats_dt[, se := unlist(lapply(boot_stats_dt$Predictor, function(x) sd(beta_dt[[x]])))]

Using the âseâ values, add columns for the lower and upper confidence limits for the coefficients to boot_stats_dt.

boot_stats_dt[, `:=`(
  lwr = Beta - 1.645*se,
  upr = Beta + 1.645*se
)]

Create a ânormalâ related data table with stats from the original OLS coefficient values with their standard errors, lower and upper confidence limits.

coef_dt <- data.table::as.data.table(crime_ols$coef_df) %>%
  .[Coef != "(Intercept)"]
normal_stats_dt <- data.table(
  Source = "Normal",
  Predictor = coef_dt$Coef,
  Beta = coef_dt$Value,
  se = coef_dt$SE,
  lwr = coef_dt$Value - 1.625*coef_dt$SE,
  upr = coef_dt$Value + 1.625*coef_dt$S
)

Row bind the âbootstrapâ and ânormalâ stats data tables and plot.

stats_dt <- rbind(boot_stats_dt, normal_stats_dt) %>%
  .[, `:=`(Predictor = as.factor(Predictor), Source = as.factor(Source))]
Code 
build_plot <- function(id, dt, predictor_names){
  plot_dt <- dt[Predictor == predictor_names[[id]],]
  hide_y_tics <- TRUE
  if(id == 1 | id == 4){
    hide_y_tics = FALSE
  }
  aplot <- RplotterPkg::create_scatter_plot(
    df = plot_dt,
    title = predictor_names[[id]],
    aes_x = "Beta",
    aes_y = "Source",
    hide_y_tics = hide_y_tics,
    rot_y_tic_label = T,
    aes_CI_lwr = "lwr",
    aes_CI_upr = "upr",
    CI_show_errorbar = T,
    CI_dir = "x",
    CI_errorbar_width = 0.2,
    CI_errorbar_color = "red",
    pts_size = 3.5,
    pts_color = "blue",
    pts_fill = "blue"
  )
}
plot_lst <- purrr::map(1:5,
                        build_plot,
                        dt = stats_dt,
                        predictor_names = coef_dt$Coef
)
layout <- list(
  plots = plot_lst,
  rows = c(1, 1, 1, 2, 2),
  cols = c(1, 2, 3, 1, 2)
)

RplotterPkg::multi_panel_grid(
  layout = layout,
  col_widths = c(6.5, 5, 5),
  row_heights = c(5, 5)
)

Take Away: As noted by Mr.Â Miller:

The ensuing plot suggests the standard errors most influenced by the heteroskedasicity in our model are those for the single family home variable and especially the percentage of the state that is white variable.
